{{also|Crow}}
==English==

[[Image:Corvus brachyrhynchos 2.jpg|thumb|A bird; a crow: ''American crow'']]
{{wikipedia}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/k…π…ô ä/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|kr≈ç}}, {{IPA|/k…πo ä/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-crow.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|…ô ä|lang=en}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|crowe|lang=enm|sc=Latn}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|crƒÅwe}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*krƒÅw≈ç}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|krie|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|kraai|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Kr√§he|lang=de}}), from {{m|gem-pro|*krƒÅhanƒÖ}} ‚Äòto crow‚Äô. See below.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[bird]], usually black, of the genus ''[[Corvus]]'', having a strong conical beak, with projecting bristles; it has a harsh, croaking call.
#* '''1922''', E.R. Eddison, ''The Worm Ouroborus''
#*: Gaslark in his splendour on the golden stairs saying adieu to those three captains and their matchless armament foredoomed to dogs and '''crows''' on Salapanta Hills.
# A bar of iron with a beak, crook, or claw; a bar of iron used as a lever; a [[crowbar]].
#* '''1796''', Matthew Lewis, ''The Monk'', Folio Society 1985, page 267:
#*: He approached the humble tomb in which Antonia reposed. He had provided himself with an iron '''crow''' and a pick-axe: but this precaution was unnecessary.
# The cry of the [[rooster]].
# A [[gangplank]] ([[corvus#Latin|corvus]]) used by the Roman navy to board enemy ships.
# {{context|among butchers|lang=en}} The [[mesentery]] of an [[animal]].

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|bar}} [[crowbar]]
* {{sense|cry of a rooster}} [[cock-a-doodle-doo]]

