===Etymology 2===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|crowen|lang=enm|sc=Latn}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|crƒÅwan}} (past tense {{m|ang|crƒìow}}, past participle {{m|ang|crƒÅwen}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*krƒÅhanƒÖ}} (compare Dutch {{term|kraaien|lang=nl}}, German {{term|kr√§hen|lang=de}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*greh‚ÇÇ-}} ‚Äòto caw, croak‚Äô (compare Lithuanian {{term|gr√≥ti|lang=lt}}, Russian {{term|–≥—Ä–∞—è—Ç—å|tr=gr√°jat'|sc=Cyrl|lang=ru}}). Related to {{m|en|croak}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|crows|crowing|crowed|past2=crew|past2_qual=UK|crowed}}

# To make the [[shrill]] [[sound]] characteristic of a rooster; to make a sound in this manner, either in joy, gaiety, or defiance.
#* Shakespeare
#*: The morning cock '''crew''' loud.
#* '''1962''', {{w|Bob Dylan}}, {{w|Don't Think Twice, It's All Right}}
#*: When your rooster '''crows''' at the break o' dawn
#*: Look out your window and I'll be gone.
# To [[shout]] in exultation or defiance; to brag.
#: ''He's been '''crowing''' all day about winning the game of cards.''
# To utter a sound expressive of joy or pleasure.
#* Tennyson
#*: the sweetest little maid that ever '''crowed''' for kisses
#* '''1913''', [[w:D. H. Lawrence|D.H. Lawrence]], ''[[s:Sons_and_Lovers|Sons and Lovers]]'', [[s:Sons and Lovers/Chapter II|chapter 2]]:
#*: Hearing the miner's footsteps, the baby would put up his arms and '''crow'''.
# {{context|music|lang=en}} To test the reed of a [[double reed]] instrument by placing the reed alone in the mouth and blowing it.

